Question T7 \'97 Algebra (proof by contradiction inequality)\
Assertion (x+a)/\uc0\u8730 (x^2+a^2) - (x+b)/\u8730 (x^2+b^2) > 0, \u2151 a,b>0, a>b, x^2>ab\
Suppose that\
(x+a)/\uc0\u8730 (x^2+a^2) - (x+b)/\u8730 (x^2+b^2) \u8804 0\
(x+a)/\uc0\u8730 (x^2+a^2) \u8804 (x+b)/\u8730 (x^2+b^2)\
As both sides are positive we may square the inequality\
(x^2+2ax+a^2)/(x^2+a^2) \uc0\u8804 (x^2+2bx+b^2)/(x^2+b^2)\
1+2ax/(x^2+a^2) \uc0\u8804 1+2bx/(x^2+b^2)\
2ax/(x^2+a^2) \uc0\u8804 2bx/(x^2+b^2)\
As 2x>0 we may also divide it\
a/(x^2+a^2) \uc0\u8804 b/(x^2+b^2)\
As the denominators are both +ve we may multiply across\
a(x^2+b^2) \uc0\u8804 b(x^2+a^2)\
ax^2+ab^2 \uc0\u8804 bx^2+ba^2\
a^2-bx^2+ab^2-a^2b \uc0\u8804 0\
x^2(a-b)-ab(a-b) \uc0\u8804 0\
(a-b)(x^2-ab)\uc0\u8804 0\
But a>b \uc0\u8658 a-b>0\
Also x^2>ab \uc0\u8658 x^2-ab>0\
(a-b)(x^2-ab)>0\
Hence by contradiction\
(x+a)/\uc0\u8730 (x^2+a^2) - (x+b)/\u8730 (x^2+b^2) > 0\
